snippet.textDisplay:
You want to understand the rationale behind this piece of excess? Watch it climb up a sand dune.

This vehicle is actually more capable in sand than some tracked vehicles. No, this is not hyperbole. This has been put to the test. It will scale a Sahara sand dune in a manner that NO armoured personnel carrier can match. Though to be fair, the reason it will scale that sand dune at over 40 mph, is because unlike the armoured personnel carrier, it isn't carrying 20 tons of armour plate. Which may be something you would prefer to have shielding you from incoming artillery shells if you're in that sort of environment. But outside of a combat zone, this vehicle's ability to traverse desert sands is on a level that makes it pretty much king of the hill for sand dune work.

The downsides? Apart from that $1.5 million price tag, you have to factor in the following:

[1] Maintenance costs: comparable to the maintenance costs of a medium sized warship. If something breaks on this, you REALLY want someone else to be paying the bill. Break the transmission on this (complete with FIVE lockable differentials) and that's a $250,000 repair bill MINIMUM.

[2] Insurance: likely to be horrendous wherever you are in the world, with the possible exception of a Gulf oil state. Here in the UK, where car insurance is draconian and penal to begin with (17 year olds are landed with a £1,000 bill for a Nissan Micra with a lawnmower engine, for crying out loud), then asking your insurance agent to take this on will cost you a king's ransom. Your insurance agent will be happy, though, because he'l be able to afford either a six week all expenses paid holiday in the Seychelles on the commission, or pay off three years of his mortgage in one go.

[3] Fuel economy: expect 5 mpg on a good day. Driving this vehicle in "I'm going to have fun" mode might drop that to 3 mpg.

[4] Shrinking violets need not apply. You will NEVER be able to drive this without attracting a bigger crowd than Scarlett Johanssen walking stark naked through your neighbourhood. The only way you could top this for show, is to turn up in your supermarket car park piloting an M1 Abrams.

A consummate choice if you're taking part in the Paris-Dakar, but ludicrous in the extreme if you're parking it in suburbia. Which pretty much sums it up.
